50|$|In {{comparison}} to plains bison (the other surviving North American subspecies/ecotype), <b>wood</b> <b>bison</b> is heavier, with large males weighing over 900 kg, {{making it the}} largest terrestrial animal in North America. The highest point of the <b>wood</b> <b>bison</b> is well ahead of its front legs, while the plains bison's highest point is directly above the front legs. <b>Wood</b> <b>bison</b> also have larger horn cores, darker and woollier pelages, and less hair on their forelegs and beards.|$|E
